What a wonderful dish! I added all of the ingredients called for in the recipe, but used less salt. The only other change I made was to roast all of the vegetables (eggplant, peppers, onion, celery and a small bulb of fennel) while the tomatoes and garlic cooked. I think that streamlined the recipe a bit. This is the best capanota I have ever made. Thanks epicurious!

Rating: 4
As other reviewers said this took a long time to make but was completely worth it. I also left out the salt at the end, there was plenty in the eggplant, capers and olives. My husband liked the caponata served warm over pasta. I like to skew it a bit mid-East by add some cumin, hot pepper and cinnamon and serving it cold with hummus and baba gounoush. Definitely worth the effort.

Rating: 4
Mindblowing!!! This recipe is a lot of work but the payoff is well worth it. I had never had caponata before but it was amazing- so much flavor for a vegetarian dish. I will definitely make this again. Absolutely amazing!!!!

Rating: 4
This is delicious! I've only ever had caponata from a jar before (disgraceful, I know), and couldn't believe how fresh and delicious this tasted! I only made a handful of changes. I didn't have a thermometer, so I just winged the frying and cooked the eggplant when the oil seemed hot- it turned out wonderfully. I actually had to stop myself from eating all the salted fried eggplant before it went into the caponata. I did not add the extra 1 tsp salt to the caponata- my eggplant was still plenty salty, my canned tomatoes had salt, and the capers and olives are salty (not to mention the celery is boiled in salted water), so I didn't want to overdo it. I tasted it the next day to see if it needed extra salt and thought it was delicious the way it was. Perhaps err on the side of less salt: you can always add more. Also, from other reviews (and personal preference), I cut way back on the olives. Even though I multiplied the recipe by 1.5 (I was cooking for a lot of people), I only put in a rounded 1/2 c of olives. Everyone loved it, even people who hate olives. Many people wanted the recipe. Will definitely make again- it may become my signature dish to bring to parties.

Rating: 4
Excellent dish and very much worth all the effort it took to make it. I'm not a fan of raisins in caponata and was glad this one didn't contain any. I love olives and thought they were perfect in the dish! I served this on lightly-toasted ciabatta rolls with fresh mozzarella for lunch. Fabulous!

Rating: 4
Outrageously good. The eggplant had a fair amount of salt left in it from the first step, so I didn't add any more salt. I had no capers, olives, celery, parsley, or basil on hand so I just left them out; replaced the red wine vinegar with balsamic; and used a bit less sugar. OK, so it doesn't seem to bear much resemblance to the original recipe, but wow was it good. And yes, I agree it's a heck of a lot of effort.

